			    STPJS 265</div>
  <p class="cont">is no wonder He is so positive in the great declaration: He that believes and is baptized shall be
  saved, and he that believes not shall be damned!<span class="footRef">1</span> There was no other name given under heaven, nor
  no other ordinance admitted, whereby men could be saved:<span class="footRef">2</span> No wonder the Apostle said, being
  &ldquo;buried with him in baptism,&rdquo;<span class="footRef">3</span> ye shall rise from the dead!<span class="footRef">4</span> No wonder Paul had to arise and be
  baptized and wash away his sins:<span class="footRef">5</span> No wonder the angel told good old Cornelius that he must send
  for Peter to learn how to be saved:<span class="footRef">6</span> Peter could baptize,<span class="footRef">7</span> and angels could not, so long as there were
  legal officers in the flesh<span class="footRef">8</span> holding the keys of the kingdom,<span class="footRef">9</span> or the authority of the priesthood.<span class="footRef">10</span>
  There is one evidence still further on this point, and that is that Jesus himself when he appeared to
  Paul on his way to Damascus,<span class="footRef">11</span> did not inform him how he could be saved.<span class="footRef">12</span> He had set in the
  church first Apostles, and secondly prophets, for the work of the ministry, perfecting of the saints,<span class="footRef">13</span>
  etc.; and as the grand rule of heaven<span class="footRef">14</span> was that nothing should ever be done on earth without
  revealing the secret to his servants the prophets, agreeably to Amos 3:7,<span class="footRef">15</span> so Paul could not learn
  so much from the Lord relative to his duty in the common salvation<span class="footRef">16</span> of man, as he could from one
  of Christ&rsquo;s ambassadors<span class="footRef">17</span> called with the same heavenly calling<span class="footRef">18</span> of the Lord, and endowed with the
  same power from on high<span class="footRef">19</span>&mdash;so that what they loosed on earth, should be loosed in heaven; and
  what they bound on earth should be bound in heaven:<span class="footRef">20</span> He, the Lord being a priest forever, after the
  order of Melchizedek,<span class="footRef">21</span> and the anointed Son of God,<span class="footRef">22</span> from before the foundation of the world,<span class="footRef">23</span>
  and they be begotten sons of Jesus<span class="footRef">24</span> through the gospel, to teach all nations&mdash;and lo I am with you
  always to the end of the world<span class="footRef">25</span>&mdash;that is&mdash;by the other comforter which the world cannot
  receive<span class="footRef">26</span>&mdash;for ye are the witnesses<span class="footRef">27</span>&mdash;having the testimony of Jesus which is the spirit of
  prophecy.<span class="footRef">28</span></p>
  <div class="topic">Necessity of Repentance</div>
  <p class="std">From what has already been introduced as testimony to prove that no man can be saved without
  baptism,<span class="footRef">29</span> it will be seen and acknowledged that if there was sin among men, repentance was as
  necessary at one time<span class="footRef">30</span> or age of the world as another&mdash;and that other foundation can no man lay
  than that is laid, which is Jesus Christ.<span class="footRef">31</span> If, then, Abel was a righteous man<span class="footRef">32</span> he had to become so
  by keeping the commandments; if</p>
